Students learn uncommon languages through LAI

By]. M. Gonzalez

For The Pitt News

Pitt’s language opportunities extend
beyond the languages most students take.

French, Spanish, Italian and Gemian are
among the commonly taught languages, yet
some uncommon languages are available to
students through the Language Acquisition
Institute.

The institute offers the Uncommonly
Taught Languages Program. Students can
request a language that is not currently
taught, provided that a native speaker can
be found to teach it.

According to Robert Henderson, director
of LAI, a native speaker can relate personal
knowledge from their country. The small
classes allow students to receive individual
attention from a native speaker rather than

9 reading about the country’s language in a

textbook, he said.

LAI was established in 1970. It was
designed to bring less commonly taught
languages and their cultures to the interests
of students.

Edward Anthony said he helped start the
institute because “Pitt was interested in the
international dimension.” He said he

believes that it makes people “aware of the
cultural, linguistic strands of our country.”

LAI tries to bring in languages unavailable
elsewhere to students. Some of the lan-
guages popular now are Arabic, Irish
Gaelic, Korean and Swahili.

Pitt senior Chris Callahan, who is taking
Thai, said he believes that “the school
should be focusing on broadening classes if
we are entering an international market.”

Reeny Davison, the Dutch instructor,
agrees on expanding language education.
“The world is a lot broader than French,
Spanish and German.”

According to the “Pittsburgh Plan for the
Study of the Uncommonly Taught
Languages,” Anthony wrote that “the faculty
recommended that  the university should
be strongly urged to strengthen its program
in the less commonly taught languages 

When the institute was founded, any stu-
dent could request a language, but
“because of budgetary constraints, ideal sit-
uations must remain destinations,” accord-
ing to Anthony.

Anthony suggested the university should
provide more funds to LAI. Although this is
difficult, universities “must acknowledge
their students and to provide linguistic tools

for research,” he said.

According to Henderson, the most com-
mon reasons students enroll in uncommon-
ly taught languages are for personal inter-
est, for communication with family mem-
bers that speak the language, to prepare for
a foreign exchange program or for research
in areas of political science,. Religious
Studies, business or archaeology.

The largest enrollment is in American
Sign Language. The majority of the students
taking it are interested in interpretation and
deaf education.

Sophomore Maureen Fox said she is
studying Irish “to bring it back into the fam-
ily” because her grandparents spoke it.

Senior John Connolly said he studies Irish
for family reasons as well. “All my family
still speaks it.”

According to Kevin McLauglin, the
instructor for Irish Gaelic, there is also
another reason so many are taking Irish. He
said, “Interest in Irish is growing because it
is becoming recognized in the Irish commu-
nity. It is officially recognized as a minor
language in the Common Market.”

