MONDAY, FEBRUARY 21, 1994

Space race not overyet

The nation’s space program has come under increas-
ing attack from those who argue that the money would
be better spent elsewhere. Some argue that the money
would be better spent at home, on Earth, and that all
of these ventures are merely “pie in the sky” attempts
at pipe dreams.

However, with the world moving ahead at a rapid
pace, it is time to look beyond the confines of the
planet. The space program is a necessary endeavor for
many reasons, not all of them scientific.

The most important reasons are scientific. As humans
attempt to survive the hostile environment of space,
hidden benefits come which help all of humanity. Most
of the technology which has come to help the handi—
capped, most notably the blind, has come from the
space program. These technological advances will also
help America retain its competitive edge in the world
of science. _

The knowledge that is to be gained about the uni-
verse by further exploration is invaluable.,It is impor-
tant to know about the universe as a whole in order to
understand very important areas of science such as
physics.

Launching" rockets and space probes is better than
launching missiles. Attempting to explore and develop
the resources outside of the Earth provide an outlet for
much of the military technology developed during the
Cold War. However, instead of using such technology
as a tool of mass destruction, it can be used to better
our lot on the planet. 1

The scientists who might otherwise peddle their
knowledge to third—world despots, who want such
weapons to use in conﬂicts with their neighbors, could
be better employed in space explorationefforts.

The United States is considering joint projects with
the former Soviet republics. This will increase the influ-
ence of the United States in a region that is becoming
increasingly important, and at the same time, increas-
ingly unstable. This is an opportunity that the country
cannot afford to miss out on. The former Soviet Union
was making great strides in important areas such as
heavy lift boosters, whichallow for the construction of
space stations and the like. By working with the for-
mer Soviets, not only can the United States raise its
clout, but it can also save money in its own space pro-
gram. With complaints about the increasing costs, a
method of cutting costs while gaining benefits should
appeal to all.

Looking to history, it was not so long ago that
President Kennedy mobilized the nation with the goal
of putting a man on the moon. With clear goals such
as a manned space station, returning to the moon and
even a possible mission to Mars, the nation can once
again regain some national focus and ‘resume its place
as a leader on the Earth and beyond.

