The Pitt women’s tennis team
hosted their invitational this
weekend taking 11 wins —— a
team record since the invitation-
al was started four years ago.

The Fourth Annual 1994
University of Pittsburgh
Women’s Tennis Invitational
took place last Friday, Saturday
and Sunday.

Pitt hosted seven teams and
the competition consisted of
single and double play with six
single flights and three double
flights.

The singles flight A champi-
onship was taken by Santi
Nalluri of Youngstown State
University.

Pitt’s Alison Baker won the
flight A consolation singles
championship. Baker defeated
Carey Sisko of Duquesne in the
final round 5-7, 6—3, 6-2.

Head coach George
Dieffenbach said that Baker had
a terrific tournament.

“She beat two players that
beat her during the season in
dual matches,” Dieffenbach
said.

Dieffenbach was also pleased
that Bakers performance
became a lot more offense-ori-
ented, playing the net more
than usual.

In flight B, Pitt"s Marla
Zielinski won her first round
against Kristen Blayney of
Cleveland State University.
However, she lost in the next
round to the University of
Akron’s Colleen Hollowell.

Hillary Gordon of Pitt com-
peted in the Flight E singles
despite illness. Gordon lost her
first round but went on to
defeat Natalie Fate of Akron
University in the semifinals with
6-2, 6-5.

Caren Lincow competed for
Pitt in the flight F singles, win-
ning the consolation champi-
onship. Lincow played Amy
Protzman of Marshall University
in the final round winning 4-6,
6-4, 7-5.

“I went out there and gave it
my best today and Ifelt like a
great player,” Lincow said.

“Caren really progressed a lot
and raised her game at least a
level this weekend,”
Dieffenbach said.

